'\" t
.TH "UvTTY-LAUNCH" "1" "" "uvtty-launch"
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.SH "NAME"
uvtty-launch - UvTTY Program Launcher
.PP
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
\fBuvtty\-launch\fR
suspends the current UvTTY frontend, and starts a program it its place on
the seat. Typically, the intended use is for starting another display
server.
.PP
By default \fBuvtty\-launch\fR uninhibits the frontend when the called
program quits, to allow the frontend to start back up again.
.PP
\fBuvtty\-launch\fR detects when there is no program using any modesetting
device on the seat. When this happens, it uninhibits, even if the process
is still running, even if \fB\-i\fP is specified. This is to prevent
commands like
.B sleep inf
from making the session unusable.
.PP
.B uvtty-launch
works similar to
.BR vtty-launch (1)
only it only works under user session UvTTYs, which are typically started
from a display manager, as opposed to a system service.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.PP
\fB\-i\fP, \fB\-\-inhibit\-after\-quit\fP
.RS 4
This option prevents \fBuvtty\-launch\fR from uninhibiting the frontend
which would otherwise allow the frontend to start up again after the
called process quits.
.RE
.PP
.SH "EXAMPLE USAGES"
.PP
.B Starting Weston:
.RS 4
uvtty-launch weston
.RE
.RS 8
or
.RE
.RS 4
uvtty-launch -- weston
.RE
.RS 8
or
.RE
.RS 4
uvtty-launch -- weston --xwayland
.RE
.PP
.B Starting Plymouth:
.RE
.RS 4
sudo plymouthd
.RE
.RS 4
uvtty-launch -i -- sudo plymouth show-splash
.RE
.PP
.RE
.B Starting X11:
.RS 4
uvtty-launch startx
.RE
.SH See Also:
.BR uvtty (7),
.BR vtty-launch (1)
